HEPATITIS E - FRANCE: (MARSEILLE) PIG LIVER SAUSAGE
***************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: Thu 17 Sep 2009 [1st submitted mid-August]
From: Philipe Colson <philippe.colson@mail.ap-hm.fr>


8 autochthonous hepatitis E cases have been diagnosed since 2007 in
the microbiology laboratory of Timone Hospital in Marseille
(southeastern France) in individuals who ate raw figatellu, a
traditional sausage of Corsica, France. Figatelli are widely consumed
in France, and they are good candidates for hepatitis E virus (HEV)
transmission because they are made with pig liver and are commonly
eaten raw.

A case-control study revealed that acute or recent HEV infection was
significantly linked with consumption of raw figatellu. Moreover,
genotype 3 HEV sequences were recovered from 7 figatelli purchased in
supermarkets in southeastern France, and genetic links were found
between these sequences and those recovered from patients who ate raw
figatellu. In each case, the delay between figatellu consumption and
hepatitis onset was compatible with the incubation period of hepatitis
E.

Autochthonous hepatitis E is an emerging disease in industrialized
countries, but the source and route of HEV infections are not known in
most cases despite increasing evidence that it is a zoonosis with pigs
as reservoirs.

In France, more than 100 autochthonous cases are notified per year.
Most of them have occurred in the South, where HEV seroprevalence was
found to be higher than in the North (16.6 percent versus 3.4 percent)
and where 7 fatal cases have been reported. Our findings have been
notified to the French public health authorities, and since May 2009,
an official policy compels the manufacturers of pig liver sausages to
recommend cooking these sausages thoroughly. Indeed, it has been shown
that cooking HEV-containing food products limits their ability to
transmit infectious HEV.

--
Philippe Colson PharmD PhD
Pole des Maladies Infectieuses et Tropicales Clinique et Biologique,
Federation de Bacteriologie-Hygiene-Virologie,
Centre Hospitalo-Universitaire Timone, AP-HM,
264, rue Saint-Pierre 13385 Marseille cedex 5, France
