<rene.gerolami@ap-hm.fr>

[ProMED-mail thanks Drs Colson and Gerolami for drawing attention to
this unique example of food-borne transmission of hepatitis E virus
(HEV) infection. We regret an inadvertent delay in posting this
meticulous report.

Although humans have been considered the natural host for HEV,
antibodies to HEV or closely related viruses have been detected in
primates and several other animal species, domestic pigs in particular.

HEV is normally considered to be transmitted via the faecal-oral
route, and hepatitis E is usually regarded as a waterborne disease.
Consumption of faecally contaminated drinking water has been the cause
of most epidemics, but the ingestion of raw or uncooked shellfish has
been the source of sporadic cases in endemic areas. To this can now be
added the consumption of raw pig liver sausages (figatellu). Indeed,
any food product derived from pig liver should not be consumed
uncooked. - Mod.CP]

[See photo of figatelli at:
<http://iledebeaute.i.l.pic.centerblog.net/p6fd1zci.jpg>
- Mod.JW]
